    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-11-24T18:32:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-11-24T18:32:00-05:00" n="185"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d185">
                <head>185. Circular Airgram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss>
                    to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Austria</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d185fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, RG 59, Records of the Department of State, Central Files,
                        1964–66, PET 3 <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss>. Confidential. Drafted
                        by <persName corresp="#p_OJG1">Oliver</persName> (FSE) and cleared by
                        Spielman (<gloss target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>/WE), Bennsky (NEA), and
                            <persName corresp="#p_EAF2">Ensor</persName> (FSE). Repeated to Algiers,
                        Baghdad, Beirut, Benghazi, Bonn, Brussels, Cairo, Caracas, Djakarta, Jidda,
                        Kuwait, Lagos, London, Ottawa, Paris, Rome, The Hague, Tehran, Tripoli, USEC
                        Brussels, USEC Luxembourg, <gloss target="#t_USRO1">USRO</gloss> Paris, and
                        the Mission in Geneva.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">CA–5671</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-11-24T18:32:00-05:00">November 24, 1965, 6:32 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>U.S. Policy Toward the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
                            (<gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss>); Contact of Embassy Officers
                        with the <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> Secretariat</item>
                </list>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>REF</head>
                    <item>Depts CA–386, July 10, 1963;<note n="2" xml:id="d185fn2">Not printed.
                            (Ibid., PET 1 <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>)</note> CA–1436, Aug. 5,
                            1963;<note n="3" xml:id="d185fn3">Not printed. (Ibid., PET 3 <gloss
                                target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss>)</note> Geneva’s A–43, July 19,
                            1963<note n="4" xml:id="d185fn4">Not printed. (Ibid., PET 1 US–<gloss
                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>)</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The referenced airgrams (copies attached)<note n="5" xml:id="d185fn5">None found
                        attached.</note> state the policy of the <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss>
                    in respect of the <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> and communications by US
                    Reps with that organization. These are forwarded for the guidance of the Embassy
                    now that the <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> is headquartered in
                    Vienna.</p>
                <p>The US–<gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> policy of neutrality and non-commitment
                    towards <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> detailed in CA–386 (paragraph 8)
                    has not prevented the <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> from obtaining
                    recognition from international organizations, specifically the <gloss
                        target="#t_ECOSOC1">ECOSOC</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_UNCTAD1"
                        >UNCTAD</gloss>, and Austria has granted diplomatic status to the
                    organization and its personnel. In light of these and other successes by the
                        <gloss target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss>, the <gloss target="#t_USG1"
                        >USG</gloss> intends to review the present policy towards the <gloss
                        target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> and consider if some other policy towards the
                    organization might more usefully serve U.S. interests. Comments from Embassy
                    Vienna and other addressees regarding U.S. policy towards the <gloss
                        target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> are welcomed. Until further notice, however,
                    the policy detailed in the referenced communications continues in effect.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
